            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Nia Azoulay\u2019s story is woven from the threads of two distinct worlds, a tapestry she wears with quiet pride in her Western Addition neighborhood. Born to a Moroccan-Jewish immigrant father who ran a small import shop and an African American mother who was a steadfast public school teacher, Nia\u2019s childhood was a mosaic of aromatic spices and the comforting warmth of Southern soul food. Her parents instilled in her a deep sense of justice and the importance of looking out for one\u2019s neighbors, values that became the bedrock of her identity.\n\nHer path seemed clear when she enrolled in the Social Work program at San Francisco State University. She was passionate, absorbing theories of community empowerment. However, in her third year, her mother was diagnosed with a fast-progressing illness. The theoretical lessons of her classes paled in comparison to the practical, heart-wrenching reality of navigating the healthcare system for someone she loved. Nia left school to become her mother's primary caregiver and advocate, a role that became her true, albeit informal, education.\n\nAfter her mother\u2019s passing, Nia was adrift but not without direction. The experience had forged her calling. She found a position as a Community Health Worker at a non-profit serving low-income families and students, just a 0.7-mile walk from her apartment. Her lack of a degree was overshadowed by her lived experience; she could translate complex medical jargon, empathize with caregiver burnout, and connect families to resources with an authenticity that couldn't be taught.\n\nNow at 39, Nia\u2019s life is deeply embedded in her community. Her daily walk to work is a ritual of familiar greetings and sidewalk check-ins. She is the calm anchor for families in crisis and a fierce advocate for students needing mental health support. While her social circle is small and close-knit, her wider family is the network of people she serves. Her dream isn't to climb a corporate ladder, but to establish a mentorship program connecting older residents with at-risk youth, creating intergenerational bonds of support. For Nia, San Francisco isn't the glittering skyline but the resilient, beating heart of the neighborhoods she walks every day, each step a reinforcement of her purpose."
